A chemical plant explosion in Jilin, China, led to benzene flowing into the Songhua River, causing major pollution.
The city of Harbin, with 3.8 million residents, faced a water supply shutdown.
China's environmental watchdog holds the company responsible for the contamination.
Measures were taken to dilute pollutants and ensure water safety.
China informed Russia of the pollution situation and pledged to minimize its impact.
Efforts to control water quality and monitor the polluted river continue.
The contaminated water is expected to reach the Sino-Russian border in about 14 days.
